05/09/2006

Denmark's Prime Minister Anders Fogh Rasmussen voiced his country's full support for Croatia's bid to join the EU and NATO, during a visit to Zagreb and meetings with Croatian counterpart Ivo Sanader and President Stipe Mesic on Monday (4 September). 
According to Rasmussen, Croatia could be a role model for the whole region in terms of reform progress and co-operation with the UN war crimes tribunal.
***
Bulgaria's President Georgi Parvanov and Russian counterpart Vladimir Putin were in Athens on Monday (4 September) for a meeting with Greek Prime Minister Costas Karamanlis. 
Talks focused on the regional oil pipeline project Bourgas-Alexandroupolis, which involves the three countries.
***
South Korean President Roh Moo-hyun arrived in Greece on Sunday (3 September) -- his first stop on an official 14-day trip to Europe and the United States. 
Roh met with President Karolos Papoulias on Monday, and meets with Prime Minister Costas Karamanlis on Tuesday. 
The South Korean president will hold talks with Romanian counterpart Traian Basescu on Wednesday and Finnish President Tarja Halonen on Thursday before attending the Asia-Europe Summit in Helsinki.
***
NATO South Wing Commander US Admiral Harry Ulrich met with Macedonian Defence Minister Lazar Elenovski and Army Chief of Staff Major General Miroslav Stojanovski on Friday (1 September) in Skopje. 
Talks focused on Macedonia's defence reforms and the country's participation in NATO missions.
***
Montenegrin Prime Minister Milo Djukanovic visited Helsinki on Friday (1 September). 
During the visit, he signed the 1975 Final Act of the Conference on Security and Co-operation in Europe, and met with Finnish President Tarja Halonen and Prime Minister Matti Vanhanen.
***
RomanianPresident Traian Basescu met with Danish Prime Minister Anders Fogh Rasmussen on Thursday (31 August). 
Talks focused on Romania's scheduled EU accession, developments in Lebanon, and Romania's deployments in Iraq and Afghanistan. 
From Bucharest, Rasmussen flew to Sofia for talks with Bulgarian counterpart Sergey Stanishev.
***
EU Enlargement Commissioner Olli Rehn arrived in Bulgaria on Friday (1 September), to make a final assessment of Sofia's progress in the accession process. 
This is his last such visit before the European Commission issues its monitoring report on 26 September.
***
Serbian Finance Minister Mladjan Dinkic held talks on Monday (4 September) with senior EU officials in Brussels. 
Focus was on the realisation of the so-called "Package Plus", a set of measures aimed to enhance Belgrade's EU integration process.
***
Romanian Prime Minister Calin Popescu Tariceanu kicked off a two-day visit to Helsinki on Monday (4 September) The visit to Finland, which currently holds the rotating EU Presidency, comes only a few weeks before the European Commission issues its next monitoring reports on Bulgaria and Romania, decisive for the two Balkan countries' EU entry date.
(Various sources 28/08/06 - 05/09/06)
